I may have missed it but I couldn't find a Supercuts along here. First time in CA and needed a haircut for a wedding. I went into a seven dollar place on reccoemedation of the reviews and asked if they were Supercuts and they said "Yes!! Come on in." <rate>4</rate>< text>
Updated on  06.13.2016:
The next day after I posted my review, the management contacted me and we had a meeting. I was given an opportunity to share my concerns in detail and get explanations on why the policies I disliked have to be in place. I was also told that my suggestions and complaints will be taken into consideration in the future. Although this does not fix my past experiences, I believe this was a big step forward and that's why I'm increasing my rating to 4 stars.

Previous review:
I used to be a student at this school.

I give 5 stars to almost all the teachers, the location and reasonable tuition fees. However, I give 1 star to most policies, staff members and their customer service skills.

Their registration system is very confusing and complicated. If you need any type of assistance, it's very difficult to reach the right person and get your questions answered. It takes many hours or days to get simple things resolved. They do not value the students' time at all and there have been numerous occasions when I felt treated like garbage.

The only person who is truly committed to helping students is Elvis.

Please keep in mind that laptops are not allowed in classrooms. Laptops can be such a great learning tool in the 21st century...

If you read manager's responses to some of the negative reviews, you'll see something like "please contact us" but there is no specific phone number, no email address and no name. Good luck trying to call them!

Unless you need a student visa, I recommend this school to people who like to waste their time.</text>

<text>I am writing this on behalf of my 87 year- old great aunt who purchased a car at Sam Linder Honda on 10/26/18.

My great aunt was rear ended in her 2007 Honda CR-V and wanted to purchase another Honda since they are such reliable cars.

She was shown a 2017 Honda HR-V EX w/ navigation (top of the line model) with 3,081 miles. She ended up purchasing the car in cash, wrote a check that day and drove home in her new car. I received a call that she bought a new car and wanted me to see it, I went to her house and saw the car.

She showed me the long, yellow paper which is referred to as the sales contract. I was surprised to see that in line 1a (cost before any tax, fees, etc) that she paid $26,487.74 for the vehicle. On the Honda website the MSRP of a new 2018 model was $26,540. A new one would be $52.26 more than a year old HR-V. She also got a 7 year/75,000 mile warranty for $2,235.

I looked in the glovebox to find the manual and discovered an envelope of papers. I assumed they were my great aunt's and gave them to her. She said it was a sales contract with another persons name on it. We discovered that the woman who purchased the car new one year before left her sales contract in the car. That concerned me being that the car was certified preowned and they didn't check the glovebox, did they check everything else under the hood? Upon opening it up I saw that on line 1a she paid $25,146.00 when the car was new with 59 miles on it and only $1,845 for the same warranty. My great aunt paid $1,341.74 MORE for the exact same car than the first owner did (excluding warranty).

My father, great aunt and I called and spoke to the general sales manager, Al Feria, who was very nice and helpful.

I asked why this car cost more than a new car and he explained that the two plants that produce the EX w/ navigation were out of commission which made that particular model in high demand due to there not being a lot of them. He said that the same day my aunt purchased two other people came in looking to buy it. I looked and found a like model without AWD for $21,500 with 11,000 miles on it.

I brought up that the dealership failed to check the glovebox and left the contract in it from the old owner. The phone disconnected shortly after stating the above but Al immediately returned my call. He said that some employee was getting written up for leaving the contract in the glovebox which is unfortunate but I would be furious if my personal information was left for people to find.

He kept asking how we can fix the situation and I said take the car back. He offered us $23,000 to take the car back which would have been a huge loss in money. I told him that we would would get back to him regarding the warranty and said I was going to post this online for others to see. He then began explaining all the great things Sam Linder does for the community and that he'd take the review personally. I politely ended the call by saying that nothing else needed to be said and I was getting frustrated.

Call it what you want, but I feel that my great aunt was taken advantage of and essentially got ripped off.<//text><rating>1<//rating>< resp>

< UserId.>
113360289054662294304</UserId.>
<Name>Enjanay Velasquez</Name>< Time>
1553995049481<//Time>
<Rating>5</Rating>< Text>
My family and I went here to use our Fun Cards we got for Christmas. We had a BLAST! My family and I got to enjoy Lazer Tag, Go-Karts racing (my children drove on the smaller kid carts and then were passengers on the big karts), mini golf, paddle boats, a bumper chair ride, the batting cages and arcade games.

For lunch we had the family pack which had 10 slices of pizza, 4 drinks some wings and a few celery sticks.

My family ended up spending 6 hours here and I know my children will be asking to go back here soon.

The service was okay. The staff were all young adults as far as I saw and didn't talk unless they had to.< /Text>

< review>
Great place to take your kids for a birthday party!  We brought our daughter here for her 7th birthday.

We purchased the ultimate birthday party package.

All of the kids enjoyed unlimited rides on the go karts, bumper cars, paddle boats, miniature golf, and laser tag!  Plus, each received a card good for $15 of arcade play.

The staff was fantastic! Everyone was very attentive and patient with our gaggle of kids running around.

The kids enjoyed pizza and cake. For the adults we were able to purchase turkey sandwich trays, boneless buffalo wings, boneless BBQ wings, green salad.

Unlimited soft drinks were included, and the adults were able to purchase a variety of draft beers if wanted.

Overall, everyone had a good time.

And, there's something really magical about not having to clean up after the party!<//review>

<Review>First, I did not drive so access to public transportation is crucial. The public bus stop was on the main street leaving us to walk three blocks. I was satisfied with the walking distance. My niece and nephew enjoyed themselves completely despite riding two attractions the entire time we were there. They were too old for the padde boats. I thought for sure they would be interested in the rock climbing wall and maybe the miniature golf but I was wrong. Speed and driving captured their attention so the bumper cars and the go carts were the only two attractions that held their fascination. I spent $75 for a ticket card which is swiped at each attraction. The place gives additional funds so I had a total of $120 to spend. My niece and nephew were also able to play some of the games in the arcade area. I spent cash for pizza and drinks another $23.00. The place was crowded hosting many children's parties. But the longest wait happen to be for the go carts. When you are in the public, expect some wait time which for all of us waiting in line was fine while we talked while watching the people and the activity.<//Review><gmapID>0x80dd4a820920bddd:0xf7f93c345c295141<//gmapID><date>1535844959673<//date><name>Karen Graves< /name></record></dataset><record>

<review>First, I did not drive so access to public transportation is crucial. The public bus stop was on the main street leaving us to walk three blocks. I was satisfied with the walking distance. My niece and nephew enjoyed themselves completely despite riding two attractions the entire time we were there. They were too old for the padde boats. I thought for sure they would be interested in the rock climbing wall and maybe the miniature golf but I was wrong. Speed and driving captured their attention so the bumper cars and the go carts were the only two attractions that held their fascination. I spent $75 for a ticket card which is swiped at each attraction. The place gives additional funds so I had a total of $120 to spend. My niece and nephew were also able to play some of the games in the arcade area. I spent cash for pizza and drinks another $23.00. The place was crowded hosting many children's parties. But the longest wait happen to be for the go carts. When you are in the public, expect some wait time which for all of us waiting in line was fine while we talked while watching the people and the activity.< /review><pictures>None< /pictures>< Response>

< Review>
Besides the staff I encountered who were all very helpful, happy and upbeat, this place wasn't worth the 30 miles I drove to get there.  I took my two and seven year old and their 10 year old cousin. With all the weight and height limitations they weren't able to ride anything together. We waited at two different "ride/attractions" for quite some time before anyone came to let the kids on. It wasn't busy, it just seemed like no one was manning their posts. Not a place for toddlers! I did more chasing him around trying to make sure he wasn't getting into anything he wasn't supposed to, wich was EVERYTHING. The paddle boats we're not what I was expecting, maybe because past experiences I have had we're never like that. They are basically oversized rubber duckies the kids paddle like a bicycle in an oversized jacuzzi. I'm not saying this place is horrible. If I lived closer to it and it was a little cheaper, it might be a go to place once every six months or so. The mini golf was cool. I'm just saying don't take little kids. Don't drive to far to get there, it's not worth that.< /Review>

<Text>Reasonable run of the mill entertainment centre. Extremely costly for what it is though.< /Text></record></dataset><record>
< review>
I went there for a friend's birthday and we had a blast there. Go karts were great, arcade had variety, and the staff there were very friendly. I would definitely recommend having a day there and getting the wristband. You can get alot more out of it than buying singular passes, unless you're there for the arcade. The arcade itself can have some steep prices for games so go in with a  plan if you're in for the tickets. Otherwise have fun.
Taking off a star for the price of food which is a tad high for my tastes compared to the quality and quantity of it for that matter. It's to be expected for an establishment like that but that doesn't excuse it. If you have a full party going on, the food might be better with the special catering, I'm not 100% sure.
Overall, good place for family fun, attentive staff and security all about, and worth the trip.</review>

< review>
it's poor. the game cards they give you don't even work. there were multiple games where my card wouldnt work no matter how many times I slid it. you have to swipe it back and forth 20x for the game to work. someone played a game which earned them 1,000 tickets, and it took the machine 5 minutes to even give them 100 tickets on their card. the terrain for mini golf is cheap and starting to come apart. the go-karts are really slow, and everyone overlapped me when I was pressing hard on the gas pedal. the lazer tag was so old, it reminded me of the 80s, because of how outdated it was. the only fun thing was the non-traditional bumper cars. for a place like that, you can definitely see why the lines were short. please don't go here, go to golfnstuff or something. oh yeah and you should clean your carpet.</review>

Came here with a pretty large group (~15 ppl). For the price, you can have a lot of fun here. Expect to spend about 3-4 hours max, though. When you pay for the day, you get mini golf, Lazer tag, gokarts and more all unlimited. There is also an arcade to win tickets or just for fun. There is also food, a little over priced, but it is food. There are also just open tables for parents/chaperones to wait while kids are off doing their own things.<//Review>
